fssh
====

my own ssh client, made from scratch! in rust btw.

i didn't use any ssh library or anything this is fully from scratch.

supports both password auth and public key auth (only ed25519 im too lazy to add
RSA), also supports hostkey verification though it doesn't store it in a file.

Usage: fssh [OPTIONS] <HOST>

Arguments:
  <HOST>

Options:
  -p, --port <PORT>          Port to connect to [default: 22]
      --algs <ALGS>          Comma-separated list of allowed ciphers
      --not-algs <NOT_ALGS>  Comma-separated list of ciphers to exclude
      --debug                Whether to debug or not
  -i, --identity <IDENTITY>  Private key to use [default: ~/.ssh/id_ed25519]
  -l, --login <LOGIN>        Username to log in with
  -h, --help                 Print help
  -V, --version              Print version

installation
============

precompiled binaries
--------------------

i only compiled it for windows x86_64, linux GNU x86_64 and apple silicon macOS
if you are not using any of those please compile it yourself.

1. go to the github release and download your binary:
        <i havent uploaded the release yet TODO TODO put the link here>
2. copy it to somewhere on PATH. make sure to name it fssh or fssh.exe
    in linux/macOS, /usr/bin will work
    in windows, look up on how to add a directory to PATH and copy the binary
3. restart your shell, you should be done


compiling it yourself
---------------------

1. install rust:
        curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
2. compile the thing for release
        cargo build --release
3. the binary is in target/release/fssh (or fssh.exe), copy it to somewhere in
   PATH.

   linux and macOS:
        sudo cp target/release/fssh /usr/bin
   windows:
    add a directory to PATH, then copy the file target/release/fssh.exe to that
    directory

compiling it for other OS
-------------------------

i use zigbuild for cross-compiling. some people like cross as well for it. you
should research it up yourself and find out what works best for you. im not
going to put a tutorial on how to cross-compile rust projects here.
